WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.060
You have to take seriously this claim on the part of the Nazi leadership

00:05.060 --> 00:07.860
that they wanted a thousand-year Reich.

00:16.640 --> 00:19.780
A thousand-year imperium is no joke.

00:20.260 --> 00:24.320
Perhaps the best-known abduction of all, and one of the earliest reported,

00:24.720 --> 00:28.980
is the abduction of a well-respected New England couple, Betty and Barney Hill.

00:28.980 --> 00:31.700
Look back at Barney Hill's original statements.

00:31.980 --> 00:36.900
The evil face, he looks like a German Nazi.

00:37.140 --> 00:39.660
Mankind has been seeking knowledge.

00:40.000 --> 00:42.740
Alan Dulles and his brother, John Foster Dulles,

00:42.960 --> 00:47.700
together with JPMorgan Chase and Rockefeller, funded the rise of the Nazis.

00:47.860 --> 00:51.060
Is the implication that there's some sort of Nazi sleeper cell

00:51.060 --> 00:54.040
undergirding American politics today?

00:54.040 --> 01:02.000
So World War II is not what we think it is.

01:02.800 --> 01:06.460
They were seeing these rocket-like things that were saucer-shaped,

01:06.580 --> 01:09.460
being launched from Spain, the Mediterranean coast, over toward America.

01:09.600 --> 01:09.820
Really?

01:10.060 --> 01:11.260
One year later, what happens?

01:11.860 --> 01:12.340
Roswell.

01:12.640 --> 01:15.320
I mean, is the idea that there is some sort of, like,

01:15.360 --> 01:19.080
Atlantean surviving remnant group that's still there?

01:19.080 --> 01:24.160
So for all we know, what's happening is that a future state of a certain culture

01:24.160 --> 01:26.060
is contacting itself in the past.

01:26.720 --> 01:29.420
Trying to pull the timeline towards itself or something.

01:29.680 --> 01:30.360
To actualize itself.

01:31.040 --> 01:32.480
Trantemporally actualize itself.

01:32.480 --> 01:40.100
Jason Reza-Giorjani, back by Popular Demand.

01:40.220 --> 01:42.240
Thank you so much for coming on.

01:42.400 --> 01:44.220
And, you know, we just launched an episode,

01:44.420 --> 01:46.280
and people are absolutely loving it.

01:46.420 --> 01:48.540
So check that out, part one.

01:49.340 --> 01:52.860
But there's so many other threads I wanted to get into,

01:52.960 --> 01:58.080
and I left that conversation thinking that there was a lot that was left kind of unsaid,

01:58.120 --> 01:59.900
and we could have gone on for hours.

01:59.900 --> 02:01.440
So I'm very excited to do this.

02:01.440 --> 02:10.240
You're one of the few thinkers I know who doesn't just sort of know a bunch of random disparate facts

02:10.240 --> 02:15.000
around the phenomenon, but tries to piece them together into some sort of coherent worldview,

02:15.140 --> 02:18.000
which is kind of a Herculean task.

02:18.660 --> 02:22.820
But you're attempting to do that, and I can't think of too many other—

02:22.820 --> 02:24.700
I mean, Jacques Vallée might be another one,

02:25.100 --> 02:27.840
but there aren't too many thinkers trying to do that.

02:28.080 --> 02:29.500
So this is very cool.

02:30.280 --> 02:30.880
Thank you.

02:30.880 --> 02:34.020
You know, that made me think of something that actually, you know,

02:34.580 --> 02:37.420
would probably be a good preface to this conversation,

02:37.420 --> 02:44.380
because I think that one of the most significant crises that we face in our civilization,

02:44.920 --> 02:49.600
and, you know, in the world at large, is the decline of philosophy.

02:49.600 --> 03:05.480
The reduction of philosophy to academic scholasticism and logic chopping and the lack of deep, serious, broad-spectrum thinking

03:05.480 --> 03:11.400
that would be capable of, for example, tackling the close-encounter phenomenon, right?

03:11.400 --> 03:17.940
I mean, obviously, it should be philosophers who are engaging, both with the data of close encounters

03:17.940 --> 03:20.580
and parapsychological data.

03:20.580 --> 03:29.900
In fact, you know, there were people in philosophy who played a fundamental role in development of parapsychology at its outset.

03:30.120 --> 03:37.720
Both William James and Henri Bergson were among the founding parapsychologists in the era of psychical research.

03:37.720 --> 03:44.220
In fact, William James was the president of the Society for Psychical Research in the 1870s.

03:44.220 --> 03:46.740
And Bergson was as well later on.

03:46.800 --> 03:47.300
I didn't know that.

03:47.300 --> 03:49.420
Either the 1910s or something like that.

03:49.440 --> 03:49.880
There you go.

03:50.120 --> 03:58.980
And this is a time when parapsychology wasn't relegated to quacky circles and, you know, new-agey conferences.

03:59.920 --> 04:05.380
Bergson was debating Einstein at the time, and so he was considered a worthy debate partner for Einstein,

04:05.380 --> 04:11.160
who himself wasn't, you know, fully accepted by mainstream science, but was very well-respected.

04:11.160 --> 04:14.160
Yes, and James had predicted...

04:14.220 --> 04:22.360
...in the era when he was the president of the Society for Psychical Research that this would be the next great scientific revolution, right?

04:22.740 --> 04:25.480
What I, in my writings, have called the spectral revolution.

04:26.080 --> 04:27.200
And it didn't happen.

04:28.200 --> 04:37.820
And, you know, in my first book, Prometheus and Atlas, I ventured a, you know, a basically theory of why it didn't happen.

04:38.480 --> 04:50.800
And that's because of the extremely serious psychological and sociological implications of mainstream acceptance of things like telepathy, precognition, clairvoyance, and so forth.

04:50.800 --> 05:03.320
And so, you know, it's not only essential for philosophers to engage with the ontological and epistemological questions inherent in parapsychological data or close encounter phenomena,

05:03.320 --> 05:07.020
but also the ethical and political ramifications.

05:07.020 --> 05:16.760
And this brings me to what I wanted to say in response to your opening, which is that I've made an argument now in several of my books

05:16.760 --> 05:28.000
that it's definitional to the type of the philosopher to develop concepts that cut across all of the major domains of philosophy,

05:28.000 --> 05:38.000
from ontology and epistemology to then an ethics and a politics that follow from that ontological and epistemic thinking.

05:38.000 --> 05:41.120
And then also, I think aesthetics is very important.

05:41.420 --> 05:48.040
From the time of Plato onward, there's been this idea that the cultivation of aesthetic discernment

05:48.040 --> 05:56.480
and the capacity to perceive the beautiful or the sublime is also another pathway to knowledge

05:56.480 --> 06:05.160
and perhaps to a kind of knowledge that transcends or undergirds reductive rationality, right?

06:05.560 --> 06:10.420
And in particular, I think that aesthetic judgment is very closely connected to ethics.

06:11.020 --> 06:14.800
And it's something that, you know, Nietzsche understood, Friedrich Nietzsche understood very well.

06:14.820 --> 06:18.100
Yeah, he says, I think there's some quote, I'm going to butcher it, but it's like,

06:18.160 --> 06:21.760
life is only eternally justified in its aesthetic form or something.

06:21.860 --> 06:24.040
And he, yeah, he fully believed that.

06:24.200 --> 06:25.260
And Nietzsche wasn't alone.

06:25.260 --> 06:36.260
I mean, look, if you, I mean, Kant is well known for being a very principled, hyper-rational advocate

06:36.260 --> 06:39.320
of this crystalline universal ethics.

06:39.800 --> 06:43.820
But if you ask me, Kant's most interesting work is his aesthetic work.

06:43.980 --> 06:47.300
And it's in his aesthetics and his third critique, critique of judgment,

06:47.780 --> 06:50.900
that you can see the connection between Kant's interest in the occult

06:50.900 --> 06:54.120
and Kant's development of this universal ethics.

06:54.120 --> 07:02.280
Then, for example, Hegel has an entire account of how you can see the evolution of human consciousness

07:02.280 --> 07:08.940
or what he called spirit through changes in aesthetic styles, changes in, you know,

07:09.200 --> 07:14.920
artistic expression from epoch to epoch and how they reflect the evolution of the perceptive

07:14.920 --> 07:17.260
and cognitive capacities of humanity.

07:17.260 --> 07:25.280
So, okay, my point is that to be a philosopher, you really have to be thinking across all of these domains

07:25.280 --> 07:34.440
and developing concepts that cut across them, above all, because you cannot have any unquestioned presuppositions.

07:34.440 --> 07:39.320
So, you could be the most brilliant, let's say, metaphysician, right?

07:39.500 --> 07:42.700
And someone who's developing a very rigorous epistemology.

07:43.860 --> 07:48.460
But if you have unquestioned political presuppositions,

07:48.820 --> 07:54.980
it's going to be tacitly warping your ontology and epistemology.

07:54.980 --> 08:02.640
And if you want to really be a philosopher, you know, which is to say someone who from the era of Socrates onward

08:02.640 --> 08:08.660
was defined by boundless, limitless, and thorough-going questioning,

08:09.040 --> 08:17.640
you really cannot give yourself the luxury of unquestioned assumptions in any area, right?

08:17.640 --> 08:21.380
So, I mean, this has very serious implications for religion, obviously,

08:21.500 --> 08:26.740
because it means that it's definitional to a philosopher that he or she,

08:27.040 --> 08:30.960
I consider Ayn Rand, for example, to be a real philosopher in this sense,

08:31.540 --> 08:34.260
he or she cannot accept any religion.

08:34.920 --> 08:40.700
It is definitional to a philosopher that you cannot adhere to a religious belief system.

08:40.700 --> 08:45.860
I mean, you are crippling yourself and you are, you know,

08:46.000 --> 08:50.280
you're basically capacity to question and develop concepts from the outset

08:50.280 --> 08:52.760
if you have any kind of a religious commitment.

08:52.920 --> 08:55.360
Would you say St. Thomas Aquinas, not a philosopher?

08:55.380 --> 08:55.780
Exactly.

08:56.000 --> 09:00.040
So, the entirety of medieval European philosophy is not philosophy.

09:00.140 --> 09:01.760
And none of these people were philosophers.

09:02.500 --> 09:06.400
And also, in Iran, you know, I spent a lot of time

09:06.400 --> 09:12.320
both studying Iran and also making significant contributions to Iranian studies.

09:12.460 --> 09:16.640
My book, Iranian Leviathan, is a tome on the history of Iran

09:16.640 --> 09:19.260
from Zarathustra to the Islamic Republic.

09:20.100 --> 09:27.880
And so, what this also means is that this whole era that's misnamed the Islamic Golden Age,

09:27.880 --> 09:33.880
which really was like an Iranian renaissance from the 900s to the 1100s,

09:33.880 --> 09:40.000
really doesn't have very many philosophers involved with it.

09:40.000 --> 09:44.860
Because these people were essentially Islamic theologians of the type of Thomas Aquinas.

09:45.000 --> 09:47.380
Like, for example, Al-Farabi.

09:48.380 --> 09:55.260
Al-Farabi goes to the extent of equating Muhammad with Plato's ideal of the philosopher king,

09:55.360 --> 09:57.020
which is an absolute travesty.

09:57.020 --> 10:03.660
The only thinkers in that era that really exemplified the type of the philosopher

10:03.660 --> 10:11.820
were, for example, Razi, whose writings almost completely were destroyed

10:11.820 --> 10:16.460
by various, you know, inquisitors later on,

10:16.520 --> 10:20.980
once the Turks came in and re-solidified Islam in Iran.

10:20.980 --> 10:25.160
And maybe Shahab al-Din Sohra Verdi.

10:25.480 --> 10:27.940
But it means that that whole period in Iran,

10:28.160 --> 10:31.520
very much like Europeans' medieval so-called philosophy,

10:32.020 --> 10:33.520
really doesn't pass muster.

10:34.120 --> 10:35.700
But why am I getting into all this?

10:35.760 --> 10:40.560
The point is that it seems almost as if we're entering another dark age now.

10:40.560 --> 10:47.700
With the lack of substantive philosophical thinking and fewer and fewer individuals

10:47.700 --> 10:53.960
who really pass muster as exemplary of the type of the philosopher

10:53.960 --> 10:56.420
in the way that, let's say, in the 20th century,

10:56.940 --> 11:00.080
we had Martin Heidegger, Jean-Paul Sartre,

11:01.440 --> 11:05.560
Ludwig Wittgenstein, and other really deep thinkers.

11:05.560 --> 11:10.760
So a philosopher can't be an extension of state power or religious power

11:10.760 --> 11:12.680
is sort of what you're getting.

11:12.800 --> 11:14.380
I mean, to play devil's advocate,

11:14.740 --> 11:17.680
you have philosophers like Leo Strauss, also mid-

11:17.680 --> 11:18.580
Not a philosopher.

11:19.080 --> 11:20.040
So you'd say not a philosopher.

11:20.080 --> 11:20.980
Strauss said so.

11:21.420 --> 11:22.640
Strauss literally said,

11:22.720 --> 11:24.580
I am not a philosopher.

11:24.820 --> 11:26.160
Do not call me a philosopher.

11:26.620 --> 11:29.900
I'm a professor of philosophy and a political thinker.

11:29.960 --> 11:33.140
But in Straussian doublespeak, that could mean I am a philosopher.

11:33.640 --> 11:34.700
He meant it.

11:34.700 --> 11:35.320
He meant it.

11:35.420 --> 11:37.940
And the more shocking thing that Strauss said was,

11:38.500 --> 11:40.440
at the same time as he made the statement,

11:40.580 --> 11:43.200
he said Martin Heidegger is the only living philosopher.

11:43.660 --> 11:47.860
Which coming from out of the mouth of a Jew is quite a striking statement, right?

11:47.860 --> 11:51.860
I mean, Heidegger having been a high-level Nazi functionary.

11:52.180 --> 11:56.180
But wouldn't a Straussian read on many past philosophers be that

11:56.180 --> 12:01.000
many of them had to exceed to kind of the conventional thought of the time,

12:01.000 --> 12:04.960
but then secretly they could hold their own kind of heretical beliefs.

12:05.960 --> 12:08.140
So like, you know, I'm trying to think of a good example.

12:08.340 --> 12:10.800
Like, it was, you know, one of the Enlightenment era, you know,

12:10.840 --> 12:14.060
Francis Bacon, not really a philosopher, kind of a philosopher.

12:14.460 --> 12:17.680
But like, you know, he would say things like, you know,

12:17.700 --> 12:21.440
we need empiricism to prove out God's secrets or to, you know,

12:21.480 --> 12:24.980
understand the divine nature of the world and reality.

12:24.980 --> 12:30.180
And the Straussian read on that is like, he's sort of a deist or an atheist,

12:30.420 --> 12:31.840
and he doesn't believe in God at all.

12:31.860 --> 12:36.020
And he's just sort of, you know, placating and paying lip service to,

12:36.280 --> 12:37.500
you know, the establishment power.

12:37.960 --> 12:40.620
Well, I think that through careful study, that could be verified.

12:40.820 --> 12:42.380
So you brought up the case of Francis Bacon.

12:42.560 --> 12:50.060
There is a theory that Will I Am Sheikh Spear is a pen name for Sir Francis Bacon.

12:50.120 --> 12:51.000
People think that, yeah.

12:51.000 --> 12:55.360
Now, if someone were to engage in an exhaustive philosophical analysis

12:55.360 --> 13:01.220
of the works of Shakespeare and be able to prove that that was indeed

13:01.220 --> 13:03.760
a literary persona of Sir Francis Bacon,

13:04.000 --> 13:08.080
then I think a very good case could be made that Francis Bacon

13:08.080 --> 13:11.100
was a first-rate philosopher because there's an ethics,

13:11.220 --> 13:13.940
there's a political philosophy in Shakespeare, you know,

13:14.080 --> 13:15.760
and you could reconstruct that.

13:15.760 --> 13:19.600
So that would be a case of an actual philosopher

13:19.600 --> 13:23.720
engaging in esoteric writing in order to express the full range of his thoughts.

13:23.900 --> 13:26.860
Do you believe that Shakespeare was, in fact, Francis Bacon?

13:26.960 --> 13:27.740
I think it's possible.

13:28.000 --> 13:29.300
I think there's an argument there.

13:29.500 --> 13:31.940
I don't have the range of Shakespeare scholarship

13:31.940 --> 13:35.440
or anywhere close to it to be able to assess that.

13:35.560 --> 13:38.660
I think it was like, you know, there are all these kind of occult references,

13:39.020 --> 13:41.720
like in King Lear or something, like these, you know,

13:41.760 --> 13:44.280
things were, forgot the exact argument.

13:44.280 --> 13:49.320
But it was like, Stratford-Upon-Avon wasn't super far from where Bacon was.

13:49.540 --> 13:53.120
And then, you know, all these things are mentioned like 33 times.

13:53.620 --> 13:54.660
And who knows?

13:55.240 --> 13:56.380
I mean, look, it's clearly...

13:56.380 --> 13:57.700
Bacon was prolific, you know.

13:57.980 --> 13:59.140
Will I am.

13:59.500 --> 14:00.440
I am Will.

14:00.920 --> 14:01.700
You know, the Will.

14:01.840 --> 14:02.320
I'm the Will.

14:03.020 --> 14:04.080
Shake Spear.

14:04.280 --> 14:05.780
The shaking of the spear, right?

14:06.020 --> 14:07.640
It's clearly a pseudonym.

14:07.960 --> 14:08.480
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

14:08.640 --> 14:11.120
For someone who was an incredible genius.

14:11.120 --> 14:15.920
So who the hell was that guy, like at that time, who was living and, you know,

14:16.040 --> 14:21.320
who maybe expressed his genius in other ways, as in the scientific writings of Bacon.

14:21.360 --> 14:22.480
And then there's the new Atlantis.

14:22.680 --> 14:23.340
Yeah, yeah.

14:23.660 --> 14:25.380
So anyway, it could be...

14:25.380 --> 14:29.720
Look, my point is this, that that's one thing.

14:29.840 --> 14:32.120
But if you're a philosopher who's...

14:32.680 --> 14:33.740
Let me rephrase that.

14:33.800 --> 14:38.120
If you're a metaphysician who's afraid to express a political philosophy

14:38.120 --> 14:42.160
because you might be persecuted by the religious authorities of the day

14:42.160 --> 14:47.800
and you just don't put pen to paper, you know, in any way,

14:47.900 --> 14:51.060
even let's say as a set of secret writings

14:51.060 --> 14:54.660
that you consign to somebody to be posthumously published,

14:54.900 --> 14:59.440
if you just never put pen to paper to express any kind of coherent political philosophy

14:59.440 --> 15:01.520
or ethics that follows from your ontology and epistemology,

15:01.580 --> 15:02.240
you're not a philosopher.

15:02.420 --> 15:03.020
You're a coward.

15:03.320 --> 15:03.760
Okay?

15:03.760 --> 15:07.000
And so, for example, in Iran, we had an example of somebody like that

15:07.000 --> 15:10.600
was Ebnesina, or as they call him Avicenna in the West.

15:10.740 --> 15:11.860
Great metaphysician.

15:14.260 --> 15:16.140
Maybe he has some ethics,

15:16.440 --> 15:19.600
but he did not develop a coherent political philosophy,

15:20.200 --> 15:23.920
which, as I see it, disqualifies him as the type of the philosopher.

15:24.280 --> 15:26.240
And he made a deathbed confession.

