And then Aristotle willingly left Athens

18:49.520 --> 18:52.180
because there was a plot to have him prosecuted also.

18:52.540 --> 18:54.720
So this is endemic to the history of philosophy.

18:55.220 --> 18:57.620
Was this pre-tutoring Alexander the Great?

18:57.840 --> 18:58.580
Or post?

18:58.900 --> 18:59.740
It was pre-

18:59.740 --> 19:01.700
Because Alexander was younger, right?

19:01.880 --> 19:03.240
And they say, by the way out,

19:03.320 --> 19:04.960
that Alexander didn't like Aristotle.

19:05.120 --> 19:05.380
Really?

19:05.620 --> 19:05.820
Yeah.

19:06.240 --> 19:07.080
Why didn't he like him?

19:09.240 --> 19:12.420
Aristotle ran a think tank

19:12.420 --> 19:15.040
in addition to being like a philosopher,

19:15.420 --> 19:18.180
you know, engaged in his own individual exploration

19:18.180 --> 19:19.760
and contemplation.

19:19.760 --> 19:23.740
He had essentially like the prototype of the Rand Corporation

19:23.740 --> 19:25.500
in classical Greece.

19:26.220 --> 19:28.640
And various other city-states would come to him

19:28.640 --> 19:32.960
and he would write their constitutions for them secretly.

19:33.440 --> 19:35.020
You know, you don't want to tell your people that

19:35.020 --> 19:37.900
their constitution comes from some guy's think tank in Athens.

19:37.980 --> 19:41.220
If you're living in Corinth or, you know, Sparta or whatever.

19:41.620 --> 19:43.420
But they would come to him and he would write this guy.

19:43.480 --> 19:45.560
And part of his political philosophy

19:45.560 --> 19:48.660
that informed his writing constitutions for various city-states

19:48.660 --> 19:51.860
was that we should always have a political pluriverse.

19:51.860 --> 19:54.860
He was very much against one unifying government.

19:55.920 --> 19:59.760
Aristotle was the first serious thinker

19:59.760 --> 20:01.960
to critique the idea of world government.

20:02.800 --> 20:05.420
And so, for example, he was very wary of the Persians

20:05.420 --> 20:08.360
who wanted to establish a kind of, you know,

20:09.140 --> 20:11.660
humanistic one world order, right?

20:12.660 --> 20:16.720
Well, Alexander actually had great reverence for the Persians.

20:16.820 --> 20:18.980
In particular, his hero was Cyrus the Great,

20:19.160 --> 20:20.440
the founder of the Persian Empire.

20:21.340 --> 20:23.280
The first thing he did when he got to Iran

20:23.280 --> 20:26.720
was he had them take him to the tomb of Cyrus

20:26.720 --> 20:28.560
so that he could pay his respects to Cyrus the Great.

20:29.640 --> 20:32.920
And eventually, Alexander became convinced

20:32.920 --> 20:34.940
that the Persians had the right worldview

20:34.940 --> 20:38.940
and that the whole Earth and all of its cultures

20:38.940 --> 20:42.400
should be unified into a single cosmopolitan order,

20:42.660 --> 20:44.680
which eventually was reflected in the culture

20:44.680 --> 20:47.420
of the city of Alexandria that was named after him in Egypt.

20:47.580 --> 20:50.140
It became like the cosmopolitan bastion of the world, right?

20:50.520 --> 20:53.040
So this is diametrically opposed to Aristotle's thinking.

20:53.980 --> 20:55.920
You know, Alexander becomes the exemplar

20:55.920 --> 20:57.280
of the idea of the one world order

20:57.280 --> 21:00.680
and, you know, Aristotle is the first critic of it.

21:01.220 --> 21:03.740
That's so fascinating when things like that happen.

21:03.740 --> 21:05.920
A modern example of that would be like

21:05.920 --> 21:08.340
George Soros and Victor Orban,

21:08.740 --> 21:10.440
who's kind of a mentee and mentor.

21:10.820 --> 21:12.960
And like Soros is obviously all about

21:12.960 --> 21:14.800
spreading as much democracy as possible.

21:15.020 --> 21:16.480
Orban was kind of his understudy.

21:16.600 --> 21:18.700
And then now, you know, it's totally split off

21:18.700 --> 21:20.760
and is, you know, basically the tip of the spear

21:20.760 --> 21:23.340
when it comes to European nationalism.

21:23.740 --> 21:24.140
Yeah.

21:24.360 --> 21:28.100
And, you know, it almost feels Shakespearean in some ways.

21:28.660 --> 21:29.900
Now, that's the other thing about

21:29.900 --> 21:31.680
the type of the philosopher,

21:31.680 --> 21:35.200
which is very dangerous,

21:35.680 --> 21:38.440
is the relationship between the philosopher and the state.

21:39.500 --> 21:41.760
Because, frankly,

21:42.100 --> 21:44.940
you cannot be a nationalist and be a philosopher.

21:45.740 --> 21:46.220
Okay?

21:46.460 --> 21:49.300
So any philosopher who seems like a nationalist,

21:49.800 --> 21:51.260
like, say, Martin Heidegger, right?

21:51.320 --> 21:53.640
Who literally was, you know, a Nazi functionary.

21:53.640 --> 21:54.100
Mm-hmm.

21:54.900 --> 21:55.980
They're engaging in,

21:56.160 --> 21:57.640
I was about to say Straussian,

21:57.820 --> 22:00.780
rather in platonic dissimulation

22:00.780 --> 22:04.840
and some kind of a noble lie.

22:05.060 --> 22:07.980
So do you think Heidegger was not a real philosopher?

22:08.540 --> 22:10.040
No, Heidegger was not a real nationalist.

22:10.220 --> 22:10.640
Was not a real nationalist.

22:10.640 --> 22:12.940
Yeah, and when you study Heidegger deeply,

22:12.940 --> 22:13.520
you see that.

22:13.600 --> 22:14.160
It's very clear.

22:14.280 --> 22:14.540
Mm-hmm.

22:14.540 --> 22:17.000
But only to someone with an esoteric eye for it

22:17.000 --> 22:19.640
and who can sync together with him on a deep level

22:19.640 --> 22:20.740
and understand what he's really saying.

22:20.840 --> 22:21.220
Mm-hmm.

22:21.300 --> 22:21.520
Right?

22:22.000 --> 22:25.760
So he was trying to use the German state

22:25.760 --> 22:27.040
in a certain way

22:27.040 --> 22:30.840
that had to do with his understanding

22:30.840 --> 22:33.380
of the threat posed to humanity

22:33.380 --> 22:34.720
by modern technology

22:34.720 --> 22:36.460
and a way that he thought

22:36.460 --> 22:38.380
that the German state could be shaped

22:38.380 --> 22:41.880
to confront the instrumentalizing

22:41.880 --> 22:44.160
and mechanizing threat of modern technology,

22:44.240 --> 22:46.380
to shepherd technological development

22:46.380 --> 22:47.520
in a certain direction

22:47.520 --> 22:52.500
that would prevent the instrumentalization

22:52.500 --> 22:55.540
of humanity and our alienation

22:55.540 --> 22:58.280
from our existential essence, right?

22:59.000 --> 23:01.260
So, but the deeper question is this,

23:01.420 --> 23:03.720
like, I mean, Socrates was executed

23:03.720 --> 23:05.320
by the Athenian state, right?

23:06.120 --> 23:09.600
And in his discourse on the arts and sciences,

23:09.840 --> 23:13.080
Jean-Jacques Rousseau says that the Athenians

23:13.080 --> 23:14.720
were justified in doing this

23:14.720 --> 23:17.680
because the guy was a menace to the social order

23:17.680 --> 23:21.840
and to the political cohesion of Athens

23:21.840 --> 23:28.460
and that any thinker has to basically reconcile himself

23:28.460 --> 23:30.860
to the sovereignty of the state

23:30.860 --> 23:35.720
and to, like, basically accommodating the social order, right?

23:36.320 --> 23:38.700
So Rousseau actually thinks the philosophers, you know,

23:38.760 --> 23:42.260
pose this, like, fundamental, you know,

23:42.480 --> 23:45.140
inimical challenge to state power.

23:45.380 --> 23:47.760
And I think that on some level he's right.

23:47.920 --> 23:49.860
But the irony also is that,

23:50.900 --> 23:52.460
especially in grave crises

23:52.460 --> 23:55.440
and what Carl Schmitt called states of emergency,

23:55.440 --> 23:58.620
I think it's also the philosophers of a people

23:58.620 --> 23:59.660
who can save a people.

24:00.620 --> 24:04.140
You know, a nation that lacks a philosopher

24:04.140 --> 24:07.380
or lacks deep thinkers in a moment of grave crisis

24:07.380 --> 24:08.940
is not going to make it.

24:09.940 --> 24:12.400
No, that feels very right to me.

24:12.920 --> 24:16.460
And it feels like the modern world has very few.

24:16.520 --> 24:19.760
I think of big philosophers today

24:19.760 --> 24:21.620
and that, you know, you're sort of one of them

24:21.620 --> 24:24.740
and then you have, you know, guys like Slavoj Zizek or whatever

24:24.740 --> 24:28.180
who's, you know, super too postmodern for my taste,

24:28.280 --> 24:30.200
but, you know, he's at least attempting.

24:30.560 --> 24:33.680
And then, I don't know, even Jordan Peterson in my mind

24:33.680 --> 24:35.560
who I think he sort of falls prey to,

24:36.020 --> 24:37.820
it's like narcissism of small differences

24:37.820 --> 24:39.380
between him and postmodernism

24:39.380 --> 24:41.800
because I think his stuff sort of melts

24:41.800 --> 24:44.060
into a postmodern gobbledygook or whatever.

24:44.180 --> 24:45.360
But he's trying.

24:45.560 --> 24:48.360
He's, you know, read all the right stuff or whatever.

24:48.360 --> 24:53.100
But there are very few philosophers who are very ambitious.

24:53.620 --> 24:56.020
You know, I think most philosophy professors at universities

24:56.020 --> 25:00.000
just give you these very conventional kind of lame,

25:00.660 --> 25:04.680
limited by modern epistemics reads

25:04.680 --> 25:06.060
of these past philosophers.

25:06.440 --> 25:07.400
And you're sort of supposed to,

25:07.700 --> 25:09.860
there's a great actually essay by Nietzsche

25:09.860 --> 25:11.660
called On History.

25:11.660 --> 25:14.420
And he talks about undigested stones of knowledge.

25:14.560 --> 25:16.480
And it feels like that's what they're just,

25:16.480 --> 25:19.460
they're just passing on these undigested stones of knowledge.

25:19.580 --> 25:20.860
They're not actually processing

25:20.860 --> 25:22.700
any of what they're saying.

25:23.020 --> 25:23.220
Yes.

25:23.400 --> 25:25.980
And that essay, that's incredibly important essay.

25:26.560 --> 25:29.220
It became fundamental to Heidegger's thinking.

25:30.060 --> 25:32.040
And Heidegger basically quotes it

25:32.040 --> 25:33.140
at the beginning of being in time.

25:33.560 --> 25:36.020
And it also has become very important to my work.

25:36.140 --> 25:38.040
In particular, that book, Iranian Leviathan,

25:38.040 --> 25:39.560
that I mentioned, the subtitle is

25:39.560 --> 25:42.340
A Monumental History of Mithra's Abode.

25:42.920 --> 25:44.620
And that term monumental history

25:44.620 --> 25:46.280
is from that essay of Nietzsche,

25:46.560 --> 25:48.240
The Uses and Abuses of History for Life.

25:48.940 --> 25:51.780
And he basically says that there's three modes of history.

25:52.120 --> 25:53.880
One is antiquarian history,

25:54.140 --> 25:55.680
which is what traditionalists do,

25:55.880 --> 25:58.160
where they glorify the past, right?

25:58.280 --> 26:00.020
And like the ultimate form of this

26:00.020 --> 26:02.400
is the Hindu or ancient Greek worldview

26:02.400 --> 26:04.400
where there was a golden age

26:04.400 --> 26:05.820
and then it decayed into a silver age

26:05.820 --> 26:06.680
and a bronze age and so on.

26:06.840 --> 26:08.960
And so history is declining, right?

26:08.960 --> 26:11.440
And all we can do is try to hold on

26:11.440 --> 26:12.580
to fragments of the past,

26:12.700 --> 26:13.880
to the better days,

26:14.020 --> 26:17.180
and to preserve as much of our heritage as possible.

26:17.280 --> 26:18.600
I mean, it's conservatism

26:18.600 --> 26:20.900
in an ontological sense.

26:22.180 --> 26:24.440
Then there's critical history,

26:24.840 --> 26:26.280
which is what these Pomo people do.

26:26.440 --> 26:28.120
Like you're just mentioning Zizek, right?

26:28.220 --> 26:30.740
Zizek is like, you know, probably, yeah,

26:30.960 --> 26:32.400
the greatest living exemplar

26:32.400 --> 26:34.220
of postmodern philosophy, right?

26:34.220 --> 26:37.760
And critical history is all about

26:37.760 --> 26:39.640
deconstructing power structures

26:39.640 --> 26:44.020
and showing how basically every institution

26:44.020 --> 26:46.360
and even every structure of knowledge

26:46.360 --> 26:49.500
was ultimately the product of a power game

26:49.500 --> 26:50.660
that somebody was playing

26:50.660 --> 26:53.460
and that it benefits either some class interest

26:53.460 --> 26:54.780
or institutional interest

26:54.780 --> 26:57.020
or, you know, is a product of rivalry

26:57.020 --> 27:00.340
between nations or ethnicities

27:00.340 --> 27:01.120
and so on and so forth.

27:01.220 --> 27:02.500
And that it's all oppressive

27:02.500 --> 27:03.860
and it should all be deconstructed.

27:03.860 --> 27:05.340
It's like pouring acid on history

27:05.340 --> 27:07.380
and the achievements of all people

27:07.380 --> 27:08.480
throughout time, right?

27:09.220 --> 27:11.480
And Nietzsche says,

27:11.600 --> 27:12.540
okay, to be fair,

27:13.060 --> 27:17.280
under really oppressive conditions

27:17.280 --> 27:20.720
that are resulting in social sterility

27:20.720 --> 27:22.580
and that are hampering innovation

27:22.580 --> 27:24.680
and novel cultural development,

27:24.820 --> 27:25.940
a little bit of critical history

27:25.940 --> 27:26.600
is a good thing

27:26.600 --> 27:28.540
because it breaks up ossified structures

27:28.540 --> 27:29.700
and it allows creativity

27:29.700 --> 27:31.340
to be unleashed again, right?

27:32.340 --> 27:34.140
So Michel Foucault is a great example.

27:34.320 --> 27:36.800
Michel Foucault is the ultimate critical historian.

27:36.960 --> 27:38.000
I mean, that was basically his project.

27:38.080 --> 27:39.300
Everything's a power game.

27:39.440 --> 27:39.560
Yeah.

27:39.720 --> 27:39.860
Yeah.

27:41.320 --> 27:43.280
And with all these histories that he engaged in,

27:43.320 --> 27:44.460
including history of sexuality,

27:44.780 --> 27:45.920
you know, history of the prison system,

27:46.060 --> 27:46.800
history of psychology,

27:46.900 --> 27:47.860
and that sort of thing.

27:47.860 --> 27:49.600
Then, in his own personal life,

27:49.680 --> 27:50.680
he sort of, you know,

27:50.740 --> 27:54.020
was kind of a pervert, to be honest.

27:54.420 --> 27:56.180
And I think it was kind of an expression

27:56.180 --> 27:58.620
of the morality that comes from that kind of work.

27:58.620 --> 28:00.360
I'll tell you what's also an expression of that

28:00.360 --> 28:02.360
is that Foucault endorsed Ayatollah Khomeini

28:02.360 --> 28:03.920
and the Islamic revolution in Iran.

28:04.140 --> 28:06.280
I mean, how lost do you have to be

28:06.280 --> 28:07.660
in postmodern nonsense

28:07.660 --> 28:09.780
that you think it's a liberation

28:09.780 --> 28:12.020
to help a misogynistic,

28:12.520 --> 28:15.360
theocratic, repressive regime come to power, right?

28:15.360 --> 28:17.980
Anyway, so that's critical history.

28:18.140 --> 28:19.940
And then the last modality of history

28:19.940 --> 28:21.840
that Nietzsche discusses in that essay,

28:21.920 --> 28:23.660
which is the one that he personally embraces

28:23.660 --> 28:24.980
and that I have,

28:25.220 --> 28:27.240
and that's been very important to my work,

28:27.240 --> 28:28.620
is monumental history,

28:28.800 --> 28:30.740
which is the idea that

28:30.740 --> 28:34.400
monumentalizing

28:34.400 --> 28:37.680
certain past achievements,

28:38.220 --> 28:41.960
turning certain historical figures into icons

28:41.960 --> 28:44.380
that can continue to provide inspiration,

28:44.380 --> 28:48.440
and having essentially a folkloric approach

28:48.440 --> 28:51.880
to one's heritage

28:51.880 --> 28:55.480
so that it doesn't become an ossified tradition,

28:55.480 --> 28:58.620
but it becomes a source of inspiration

28:58.620 --> 29:03.680
where you can dynamically adopt

29:03.680 --> 29:06.440
and adapt your heritage for future development.

29:07.160 --> 29:09.360
That's vital to the life of a people.

29:09.540 --> 29:11.560
And he says that it's like, you know,

29:11.560 --> 29:14.440
a tree whose branches can only grow

29:14.440 --> 29:15.960
toward the sun of destiny

29:15.960 --> 29:18.320
if it's deeply rooted in the earth

29:18.320 --> 29:20.100
and its roots are healthy underground.

29:20.340 --> 29:22.460
And that underground is the subconscious.

29:23.160 --> 29:23.800
It's that, you know,

29:23.880 --> 29:25.980
monumental history is nourished

29:25.980 --> 29:27.240
from out of the subconscious.

29:27.660 --> 29:30.140
And not everything in the past of a people

29:30.140 --> 29:33.520
has to be or should be

29:33.520 --> 29:36.140
rationally dissected and understood

29:36.140 --> 29:39.820
that we need to maintain

29:39.820 --> 29:41.700
a kind of subconscious connection

29:41.700 --> 29:43.320
to the mythic substratum

29:43.320 --> 29:44.760
of our heritage

29:44.760 --> 29:48.660
as a wellspring for continued creativity,

29:48.660 --> 29:50.200
both in the arts and the sciences.

29:51.200 --> 29:52.480
Yeah, I love that.

29:52.620 --> 29:54.440
He's so inspiring when you read him.

29:54.540 --> 29:55.520
I like, you know,

29:55.580 --> 29:57.080
he seems very irrational

29:57.080 --> 29:58.500
and kind of iconoclastic

29:58.500 --> 30:01.120
and maybe a little crazy,

30:01.260 --> 30:02.840
you know, in his personal life and stuff.

30:03.140 --> 30:04.740
And Nietzsche was almost

30:04.740 --> 30:06.300
like the first incel or something.

30:06.820 --> 30:08.940
But he was also just so inspiring.

30:09.080 --> 30:10.000
You read his work

30:10.000 --> 30:12.440
and it's full of vitality and life.

30:12.860 --> 30:14.480
So it felt like this weird juxtaposition.

30:14.640 --> 30:15.360
You had his, you know,

30:15.360 --> 30:16.280
his kind of personal life,

30:16.320 --> 30:17.180
which he was kind of, you know,

30:17.240 --> 30:17.940
withering away.

30:18.100 --> 30:19.760
And then you have the writing,

30:19.900 --> 30:21.240
which was so vital.

30:21.680 --> 30:22.000
I love him.

30:22.000 --> 30:23.680
I feel a very deep affinity to Nietzsche.

30:23.900 --> 30:27.440
I'd say Plato, Nietzsche, and Heidegger

30:27.440 --> 30:28.960
are probably the three philosophers

30:28.960 --> 30:30.980
who've most deeply impacted my own thinking.

30:31.800 --> 30:33.260
Well, you mentioned the RAND Corporation.

30:33.440 --> 30:34.700
We're in Santa Monica right now

30:34.700 --> 30:36.220
near the RAND Corporation.

30:36.380 --> 30:38.720
I believe RAND stands for R&D,

30:38.860 --> 30:39.820
Research and Development.

30:40.280 --> 30:42.120
It was formed in, I believe,

30:42.200 --> 30:43.640
the mid to late 50s.

30:44.100 --> 30:45.980
One of these sort of federally funded

30:45.980 --> 30:47.420
research and development centers

30:47.420 --> 30:49.500
that was meant to look into

30:49.500 --> 30:51.760
all sorts of issues of national security.

30:52.400 --> 30:53.100
It's kind of a, you know,

30:53.140 --> 30:54.600
it's as when we talk about

30:54.600 --> 30:55.760
the proverbial deep state,

30:55.760 --> 30:57.680
you think of the RAND Corporation

30:57.680 --> 30:59.760
and a man who was offered

30:59.760 --> 31:01.760
to be president of the RAND Corporation.

31:02.120 --> 31:03.180
Some people might not know this

31:03.180 --> 31:05.460
is a past interviewee of mine,

31:05.820 --> 31:06.900
a guy named Harold Malmgren,

31:07.260 --> 31:09.300
who was a senior presidential advisor

31:09.300 --> 31:11.440
for JFK, LBJ, Nixon, and Ford,

31:12.080 --> 31:16.600
and said all sorts of really bombshell stuff

31:16.600 --> 31:17.740
when it came to UFOs,

31:17.780 --> 31:20.080
including he held pieces of a UFO

31:20.080 --> 31:23.280
at Sandia Complex in New Mexico.

31:23.280 --> 31:25.940
It was given to him by Lawrence Preston Geis,

31:26.040 --> 31:28.420
who's Jeff Bezos' maternal grandfather,

31:28.980 --> 31:30.220
which is fascinating.

31:30.760 --> 31:33.040
And he talked about the Magenta crash,

31:33.240 --> 31:33.900
Malmgren did,

31:34.300 --> 31:36.400
and his mentor, Richard Bissell,

31:36.460 --> 31:37.800
who founded Area 51,

31:38.680 --> 31:40.580
briefing him on otherworldly technologies.

31:41.080 --> 31:42.620
Yeah, what else did Richard Bissell tell you?

31:42.880 --> 31:45.540
He said this didn't start last week.

31:45.800 --> 31:47.160
This has been going on,

31:47.160 --> 31:52.200
he mentioned 1933 Magenta.

31:52.580 --> 31:53.140
He did?

31:53.600 --> 31:53.940
Yes.

31:54.040 --> 31:55.220
Richard Bissell mentioned

31:55.220 --> 31:56.720
the 1933 Magenta crash?

31:56.720 --> 31:57.460
Yes, yes.

31:57.540 --> 31:58.580
That's amazing.

31:59.200 --> 32:01.480
So this provided a lot of backup

32:01.480 --> 32:02.880
for David Grush's,

32:03.000 --> 32:05.180
you know, famous UFO whistleblower

32:05.180 --> 32:06.440
who's responsible for a lot

32:06.440 --> 32:07.840
of modern disclosure today.

32:08.360 --> 32:10.820
His testimony around this Magenta crash,

32:10.940 --> 32:12.080
where he came out,

32:12.120 --> 32:13.200
he said that there are covert

32:13.200 --> 32:15.540
American UFO reverse engineering programs,

32:15.600 --> 32:17.060
we have this whole history on this stuff,

32:17.160 --> 32:18.820
but he also said,

32:19.260 --> 32:20.920
he talked about one specific crash,

32:20.960 --> 32:22.000
and it wasn't Roswell,

32:22.160 --> 32:25.800
it was this 1933 Lombardy,

32:25.880 --> 32:27.760
you know, northern Italy crash,

32:28.000 --> 32:29.620
